dataset_description.json.Name: Monetary Incentive Delay task
Funding: This work was supported by a Neurochoice Initiative Big Ideas grant from Stanford’s Wu Tsai Neurosciences Institute, as well as a National Institute of Health Grant 5P50DA04201205 to BK.
ReferencesAndLinks: Srirangarajan, T., Mortazavi, L., Bortolini, T., Moll, J., & Knutson, B. (2021). Multi‐band FMRI compromises detection of mesolimbic reward responses. NeuroImage, 244, 118617. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuroimage.2021.118617

trial.Description: The trial number. Each run of the task includes 72 trials, 12 from each trial type.

trial_type.Description: Indicator of the amount of money that could be won or lost during the trial

Levels.+$5: A trial starting with a high gain cue, i.e., circle with with a line positioned in the top half, indicates that if the button is pressed within the time that the target is on the screen, $5 can be gained.
Levels.+$1: A trial starting with a low gain cue, i.e., circle with with a line positioned in the middle, indicates that if the button is pressed within the time that the target is on the screen, $1 can be gained.
Levels.+$0: A control trial in the gain domain. A trial starting with a non-gain cue, i.e., circle with with a line positioned in the lower half, indicates that if the button is pressed within the time that the target is on the screen, $0 can be gained.
Levels.-$0: A control trial in the loss domain. A trial starting with a non-loss cue, i.e., square with with a line positioned in the lower half, indicates that if the button is pressed within the time that the target is on the screen, the participant can avoid losing $0.
Levels.-$1: A trial starting with a low loss cue, i.e., square with with a line positioned in the middle, indicates that if the button is pressed within the time that the target is on the screen, the participant can avoid losing $1.
Levels.-$5: A trial starting with a high loss cue, i.e., square with with a line positioned in the lower half, indicates that if the button is pressed within the time that the target is on the screen, the participant can avoid losing $5.

target_s.Description: The target appears on the screen for this amount of time. The participant should hit the button while the target is on the screen in order to have a successful trial. Note that the timing of the target is adaptive such that participants hit roughly 66% the trials in each trial type in each run.

response_time.Description: Time from the appearance of the target until participant's button press on the successful trials. On unsuccessful trials, the value is -1.

hit.Description: This variable indicates the success of the trial, i.e., if the participant hit the button while it was on the screen.

Levels.0: Missed target, i.e., response time is longer than target duration. This leads to an undesirable trial outcome (not winning money or losing money).
Levels.1: Hit target, i.e., response time is shorter than target duration. This leads to a desirable trial outcome (winning money or avoiding losing money).

total_gain.Description: Cumulative total money gaines during this task run

iti.Description: Variable inter-trial interval after the outcome presentation and the onset of the next trial

README: The goal of this experiment was to test the effects of simultaneous multi-slice imaging (or multi-band acquisition) on detectability of fMRI signal in the mesolimbic reward circuitry. In this dataset, participants performed three runs of the Monetary Incentive Delay Task within the same session each acquired with either single-slice, multi-band factor of 4, or multi-band factor of 8. The order of the runs were counterbalanced across participants.
